0^2)\n        params[8] : quadratic velocity term (x1^2)\n        params[9] : fractional power velocity damping-like term sign(x1)*|x1|^{5/3}\n        params[10]: mixed nonlinear term x0 * x1^2\n        params[11]: mixed nonlinear term x0^3 * x1\n\n    Returns:\n    - y: acceleration as a numpy array of same shape as inputs.\n    """\n    \n    if len(params) < MAX_NPARAMS:\n        raise ValueError(f"Parameter array \'params\' must have at least {MAX_NPARAMS} elements.")\n    \n    # Extract parameters for readability\n    p = params\n    \n    # Compute fractional power velocity damping-like term safely\n    vel_frac_term = np.sign(x1) * np.abs(x1)**(5/3)\n\n    # Construct the acceleration expression combining linear, quadratic, cubic,\n    # and mixed nonlinear terms consistent with the analysis.\n    \n    y = (\n          p[0]\n        + p[1]*x0                    # linear stiffness restoring force ~ -k*x\n        + p[2]*x1                    # linear damping/driving ~ -c*v\n        + p[3]*x0**3                 # cubic stiffness nonlinearity\n        + p[4]*x1**3                 # cubic velocity nonlinearity in damping/driving\n        + p[5]*x0*x1                 # mixed nonlinear coupling between position and velocity\n        + p[6]*(x0**2)*x1            # higher order mixed nonlinear coupling\n        + p[7]*x0**2                 # quadratic position asymmetry/stiffness effect\n        + p[8]*x1**2                 # quadratic velocity effect on acceleration/damping asymmetry\n        + p[9]*vel_frac_term         # fractional power damping-like effect on velocity \n        + p[10]*x0*(x1**2)           # another form of mixed nonlinearity coupling position & squared velocity \n        + p[11]*(x0**3)*x1           # higher order mixed nonlinearity coupling cubic position & velocity \n       )\n    \n    return y\n```\n\n---\n\n### Explanation:\n\n- The function `equation_v1` extends the simple linear model `equation_v0` by adding all relevant polynomial and fractional power terms described in the analysis.\n- It includes linear terms in `x0` and `x1`, quadratic and cubic powers of both variables, plus several cross terms mixing powers of `x0` and `x1`.\n- The fractional power term involving `sign(x)` and `|x|^{5/3}` captures complex asymmetric damping effects related to velocity.\n- A parameter length check ensures safe access to all coefficients.\n- This skeleton matches the physical interpretation of a nonlinear oscillator with asymmetric restoring forces and state-dependent damping/driving.\n\nYou can now fit or optimize the parameters array `params` to your data using this flexible function skeleton.', 'Based on the analysis, the acceleration \\( y \\) in oscillator1 depends on position \\( x_0 \\) and velocity \\( x_1 \\) through a combination of linear, quadratic, cubic, and mixed nonlinear terms. The key points are:\n\n- Linear terms: \\( \\text{params}[1] \\cdot x_0 \\) (restoring force), \\( \\text{params}[2] \\cdot x_1 \\) (linear damping/driving)\n- Quadratic terms: \\( \\text{params}[7] \\cdot x_0^2 \\), \\( \\text{params}[8] \\cdot x_1^2 \\)\n- Cubic terms: \\( \\text{params}[3] \\cdot x_0^3 \\), \\( \\text{params}[4] \\cdot x_1^3 \\)\n- Fractional power velocity term: \\( \\text{params}[9] * sign(x_1) * |x_1|^{5/3} \\)\n- Mixed nonlinear terms involving products like \\( x_0 x_1, x_0^2 x_1, x_0 x_1^2\\), etc., presumably at params[5], params[6], params[10], params[11]\n\n---\n\n### Here is a function skeleton `equation_v1` that incorporates these insights:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\nMAX_NPARAMS = 12\n\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """\n    Calculate acceleration y in a nonlinear harmonic oscillator given position (x0) and velocity (x1).\n\n    Parameters:\n    - x0 (np.ndarray): Position array\n    - x1 (np.ndarray): Velocity array\n    - params (np.ndarray): Parameter array with at least 12 elements\n    \n    Returns:\n    - y (np.ndarra